a 1465–1562","1465–1562":"1465–1562","1460–1510":"1460–1510","1480–1547":"1480–1547","1483–1518":"1483–1518","1486–1539":"1486–1539","–Male":"Overleden","about 1480":"circa 1480","1483":"1483","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","22 December 1510":"22 december 1510","1558":"1558","1547":"1547","Abt 1465":"circa 1465","1510":"1510","1465":"1465","1486":"1486","1562":"1562","1518":"1518","1539":"1539","1549":"1549","December 1547":"december 1547","Broadwindsor, Dorset, England":"Broadwindsor, Dorset, England","Camborne, Cornwall, England":"Camborne, Cornwall, England"},"en":{"Abt 1465–1562":"about 1465–1562","1465–1562":"1465–1562","1460–1510":"1460–1510","1480–1547":"1480–1547","1483–1518":"1483–1518","1486–1539":"1486–1539","–Male":"Deceased","about 1480":"about 1480","1483":"1483","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","22 December 1510":"22 December 1510","1558":"1558","1547":"1547","Abt 1465":"about 1465","1510":"1510","1465":"1465","1486":"1486","1562":"1562","1518":"1518","1539":"1539","1549":"1549","December 1547":"December 1547","Broadwindsor, Dorset, England":"Broadwindsor, Dorset, England","Camborne, Cornwall, England":"Camborne, Cornwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Friz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Muslim (mainly Pakistan and Bangladesh): from the Arabic personal name <i>Faiḍ</i>, from <i>fā’iḍ</i> ‘bounteous, generous’."],"variants":[{"name":"Faizi","meanings":["Muslim (mainly Afghanistan and Pakistan): surname denoting descent from or association with someone called   Faiz  ."]}]},{"name":"Anthony","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and West Indian (mainly Antigua and Barbuda, Saint Lucia, and Trinidad and Tobago, also Dutch Caribbean): from the personal name <i>Anthony</i>, Latin <i>Antonius</i>, which, with its variants and cognates, is one of the commonest personal names in Europe. Spellings with <i>-h-</i>, which first appear in English in the 16th century and in French (as <i>Anthoine</i>) at about the same time, are due to the erroneous belief that the name derives from Greek <i>anthos</i> ‘flower’. The popularity of the personal name in Christendom is largely due to the cult of the Egyptian hermit Saint Anthony (  AD  251–356), who in his old age gathered a community of hermits around him, and for that reason is regarded by some as the founder of monasticism. It was further increased by the fame of Saint Anthony of Padua (1195–1231), who long enjoyed a great popular cult and who is believed to help people find lost things. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates and derivatives (patronymics) from other languages, for example Greek patronymic   Antoniades  , Italian   Antoni  , Polish   Antoniewicz  , Croatian and Serbian <b>Antonović</b> (see   Antonovich  ) and <b>Antunović</b>; see also below. The name <i>Anthony</i> is also found among Christians in southern India, but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. Compare   Antony  .","German, Flemish, and French (mainly Alsace): Latinized (humanistic) patronymic from local equivalents of the Latin personal name <i>Antonius</i>, from its genitive form <i>Antoni(i)</i>. In North America, this surname is also an altered form of the German, Dutch, French, and Slovak cognates   Antoni   1 and   Antony   2.","History: John Anthony of Hampstead, Middlesex, England (now part of north London) migrated to Boston, MA, in 1634. By 1640 he had moved to Providence, RI, where his descendants are still established."],"variants":[{"name":"Anthes","meanings":["German: from a vernacular form, common in the Rhineland, of the personal name <i>Anton</i>, Latin <i>Antonius</i> (see   Anthony  ), a variant of   Antes   1. Compare   Anthis   1 and   Antis   1.","Americanized form of Greek   Anthis   2."]},{"name":"Anton","meanings":["German, Scottish, English, and Romanian; Spanish (<b>Antón</b>); Polish (mainly <b>Antoń</b>); Czech (also <b>Antoň</b>): from a vernacular form of the Latin personal name <i>Antonius</i> (see   Anthony  ). This surname is also found in France (mainly Lorraine).","American shortened form of various patronymics and other derivatives from the equivalents of the Latin personal name <i>Antonius</i>, e.g. Greek   Antoniades   (compare   Anthon   2), Polish   Antonowicz  , Slovenian <b>Antončič</b> and <b>Antonič</b> (see   Antonich  )."]},{"name":"Antes","meanings":["German: from a vernacular form, common in the Rhineland, of the personal name <i>Anton</i>, Latin <i>Antonius</i> (see   Anthony  ), a variant of   Anthes   1.","German: humanistic surname, a Hellenization of <b>Blume</b>, literally ‘flower’ (see   Blum  ), with reference to the Greek vocabulary word <i>anthos</i> ‘flower’. Compare   Andes   and   Andis  .","Dutch: from the personal name <i>Ant(e)</i>, a short form of the ancient Germanic names such as <i>Andbert</i>, with genitive inflection <i>-s</i>. Alternatively, perhaps a variant of <b>Antens</b>, itself possibly from a vernacular form of <b>Antoons</b>, a patronymic from <i>Antonius</i> (see   Anton  )."]},{"name":"Antczak","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Jerzy, Tadeusz, Agnieszka, Ewa, Halina, Jadwiga, Mietek, Mikolaj.","Polish: patronymic from a pet form of the personal name<i>Antoni</i> (see   Anthony  )."]},{"name":"Antal","meanings":["Hungarian and Slovak: from the personal name <i>Antal</i>, a Hungarian form of Latin <i>Antonius</i> (see   Anthony  ). This surname is also found in Romania, Czechia, Serbia, and Croatia."]},{"name":"Antoniades","meanings":["Greek: patronymic from the personal name <i>Antōni(o)s</i> (see   Anthony  ). The suffix <i>-ades</i> is classical (a variant of <i>-ides</i>, meaning ‘son/descendant of’), and was revived in the 19th century, in particular by Greeks from Asia Minor and Eastern Thrace."]},{"name":"Antonacci","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Gino, Angelo, Gaetano, Natale, Pasquale, Sal, Beniamino, Domenic, Filomena, Giuseppe, Giuseppe, Leonardo.","Italian (southern): patronymic or plural form of a derivative of the personal name <i>Antonio</i> (see   Anthony  )."]},{"name":"Antoine","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Jacques, Michel, Pierre, Francoise, Jean Claude, Marcel, Pascal, Patrice, Ancil, Andre, Camille.","French, Walloon, and West Indian (mainly Haiti): from the personal name <i>Antoine</i>, a French equivalent of   Anthony  . This surname was brought to the US mostly from Haiti. Compare   Antwine  ."]},{"name":"Antkowiak","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Danuta, Casimir, Tadeusz, Wieslawa.","Polish: patronymic from a pet form of the personal name<i>Antoni</i> (see   Anthony  )."]},{"name":"Andonian","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Armenian Aram, Aris, Garbis, Hagop, Haig, Hratch, Kevork, Kourken, Krikor, Mihran, Sarkes, Shahen.","Armenian: patronymic from the personal name <i>Andon</i>, western Armenian form of   Anthony  . Compare   Antonyan  ."]}]},{"name":"Margery","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual medieval vernacular form of   Margaret   (now also commonly spelled   Marjorie  ). This form of the name is preserved in the nursery rhyme ‘See-saw, Margery Daw’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":84,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":93,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Margery Friz Anthony was born about 1465, in Broadwindsor, Dorset, England as the daughter of Widdowe Huchyn. She had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with John Huchyn. She died in 1562, at the age of 98."},"et":{"Abt 1465–1562":"umbes 1465–1562","1465–1562":"1465–1562","1460–1510":"1460–1510","1480–1547":"1480–1547","1483–1518":"1483–1518","1486–1539":"1486–1539","–Male":"Surnud","about 1480":"umbes 1480","1483":"1483","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","22 December 1510":"22. detsember 1510","1558":"1558","1547":"1547","Abt 1465":"umbes 1465","1510":"1510","1465":"1465","1486":"1486","1562":"1562","1518":"1518","1539":"1539","1549":"1549","December 1547":"detsember 1547","Broadwindsor, Dorset, England":"Broadwindsor, Dorset, England","Camborne, Cornwall, England":"Camborne, Cornwall, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1465–1562":"noin 1465–1562","1465–1562":"1465–1562","1460–1510":"1460–1510","1480–1547":"1480–1547","1483–1518":"1483–1518","1486–1539":"1486–1539","–Male":"Kuollut","about 1480":"noin 1480","1483":"1483","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","22 December 1510":"22. joulukuuta 1510","1558":"1558","1547":"1547","Abt 1465":"noin 1465","1510":"1510","1465":"1465","1486":"1486","1562":"1562","1518":"1518","1539":"1539","1549":"1549","December 1547":"joulukuu 1547","Broadwindsor, Dorset, England":"Broadwindsor, Dorset, England","Camborne, Cornwall, England":"Camborne, Cornwall, England"},"fr":{"Abt 1465–1562":"environ 1465–1562","1465–1562":"1465–1562"